# Consistency and failure model

WatchAgent is a single process over a single SQLite file, but it has one real
distributed boundary — **WatchAgent ↔ Open-Meteo** — and a set of consistency
invariants that several features (dedup, backfill, replay) silently rely on.
Changing any of these can break correctness without breaking a test you wrote,
so treat them as contracts.

## CAP trade-off (chosen deliberately)

- **Toward Open-Meteo we choose Availability + Partition tolerance (AP).** When
  the upstream is unreachable, the poller retries with backoff and ultimately
  returns `None` — it never crashes and the API keeps serving stored data
  (`poller-error-handling.mdc`). We accept staleness (sacrifice C); Open-Meteo
  only refreshes hourly anyway.
- **Our own store is effectively CP on one node.** SQLite WAL gives
  single-writer / multi-reader linearizable access. The single file/process is
  a deliberate single point of failure for this challenge; do not pretend it is
  highly available.

## Invariants (do not regress)

- **Writes are idempotent.** `UNIQUE(city, observed_at)` + `INSERT OR IGNORE`
  turns at-least-once polling into effectively-once storage. Do not replace this
  with a plain `INSERT`, and keep `(city, observed_at)` as the dedup key.
- **Event time, not wall-clock time.** Order, dedup, and cooldown all key off a
  reading's `observed_at`, never `fetched_at` or `datetime.now()`. This is what
  makes `scripts/backfill.py` and the replay skill produce the same events the
  live poller would. New detectors and queries must preserve this.
- **Reads tolerate staleness.** API routes serve whatever is in `Storage`; never
  trigger a synchronous Open-Meteo fetch from a request handler. Freshness is the
  poller's job.
- **Single writer.** Only the poller writes. The WAL single-writer assumption and
  the cooldown read-modify-write (read `last_event_at`, then `store_events`) are
  not safe across multiple writer processes. If you ever scale out, this is the
  assumption that breaks first — call it out rather than silently violating it.

## Why this lives in a rule

These guarantees are spread across `storage.py`, `events.py`, `poller.py`,
`scripts/backfill.py`, and the skills. No single file makes the contract obvious,
so it is easy to "optimise" one of them (e.g. dedup on `fetched_at`, or fetch on
read) and quietly break replay determinism or duplicate suppression.
